            semester: 'fall 2023',
            review: "Background: Working in ML for 5 years and 10 years of overall experience. Prior course taken: AI4T, SAT, DL, CN, AI, QC. I scored A (99%) in this course.\nLectures: The course offered a robust syllabus, though the material was extensive. I appreciate the professor's teaching style. Linear algebra prerequisite is required to understand the concepts.\nProblem Sets (70%): Setting up the environment was easy. I was using conda in MacBook for all PSs and project work. Each assignment has two multiple parts with two sections: code and report submission. The code section is auto-graded. . While the instructions provided for each assignment were acceptable, they were not as clear as in other courses. Sometimes, GS errors lacked informativeness, requiring us to debug independently. The time-intensive process of tuning the algorithm contributed significantly to the difficulty of the assignments. Additionally, developing the code and generating plots for the report consumed a substantial amount of time. I tried to gain the extra credit wherever possible because I wanted to be in less stressful situation towards the end of course.\nProject (15 %): The project component involved selecting one of four open-ended topics. Given a set of packages to use in a condo environment, the task was to produce a concise report within a six-page limit. We had a rubric to follow, which gave us some guidance and goals to work towards.\nExam (13%):  We had a week to finish a 1.5-hour exam, and the unique part was that we could use our books and the internet. The test had 35 questions, each worth one mark. After completing it, we got feedback right away, although the correct answers weren't revealed. It wasn't too focused on math; understanding the concepts was key. Just going through the lectures was usually enough to score above 30.\nMandatory Quiz (2%) : Getting an easy 2% was as simple as attending the policy quiz. No major effort required.\nConclusion: Even though I dedicated over 24 hours a week to the course, the learning experience was rich both theoretically and practically. I think it's possible to achieve an A grade with around 20 hours of effort per week. The syllabus was comprehensive, covering basics to advanced machine learning techniques. I advise against pairing this course with any other course if you have a full-time job. Unfortunately, I couldn't begin the project early due to personal reasons, leading to some last-minute crunch for project completion. I didn't attend office hours, but staying active in online study groups and checking platforms like Ed helped me address project-related queries and doubts effectively. Despite its challenges, the course proved tough but ultimately rewarding.",
